 {"id":"asupersync-553y","title":"Implement Registration handle with RAII deregistration","description":"# Task: Implement Registration Handle with RAII Deregistration

## What

Create a `Registration` type that represents an active I/O registration with the reactor. When dropped, it automatically deregisters from the reactor.

## Location

`src/runtime/reactor/registration.rs` (new file)

## Design

```rust
/// Handle to an active I/O source registration.
///
/// Dropping a Registration automatically deregisters from the reactor.
/// This ensures no leaked registrations and is cancel-safe.
pub struct Registration {
    /// Token identifying this registration in the reactor's slab
    token: Token,
    /// Weak reference to reactor (allows safe drop if reactor gone)
    reactor: Weak<dyn ReactorInner>,
    /// Current interest (for modify operations)
    interest: Cell<Interest>,
}

impl Registration {
    /// Create a new registration (called by Reactor::register)
    pub(crate) fn new(token: Token, reactor: Weak<dyn ReactorInner>, interest: Interest) -> Self;

    /// Get the token for this registration
    pub fn token(&self) -> Token;

    /// Modify the interest set for this registration
    pub fn set_interest(&self, interest: Interest) -> io::Result<()>;

    /// Check if the registration is still active
    pub fn is_active(&self) -> bool;
}

impl Drop for Registration {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        if let Some(reactor) = self.reactor.upgrade() {
            // Deregister, ignoring errors (source may already be gone)
            let _ = reactor.deregister_by_token(self.token);
        }
    }
}

// Registration is !Send + !Sync because it's tied to a specific reactor
impl !Send for Registration {}
impl !Sync for Registration {}
```

## Cancel-Safety

This design is critical for cancel-correctness:

1. When a task is cancelled, its I/O futures are dropped
2. Dropping futures drops their Registration
3. Registration::drop() deregisters from reactor
4. No dangling registrations, no wakeup of dead tasks

## Why Weak<dyn ReactorInner>

- Reactor might be dropped before all registrations
- Weak reference allows graceful handling
- No panics on drop, just no-op if reactor gone

## Alternative: Token-Only Registration

Could make Registration just a Token, with explicit deregister(). Rejected because:
- Easy to forget deregister() → leaked registrations
- Not exception-safe
- Harder to reason about lifetimes

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Registration type with RAII deregistration
- [ ] set_interest() for modifying readiness interest
- [ ] Weak reactor reference for safe drop
- [ ] !Send + !Sync markers (registration is thread-local)
- [ ] Tests:
  - Drop deregisters
  - set_interest updates reactor
  - Handles reactor being gone","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"OpusNova","owner":"jeff141421@gmail.com","created_at":"2026-01-18T05:40:49.211311361Z","created_by":"Dicklesworthstone","updated_at":"2026-01-18T17:16:26.415372509Z","closed_at":"2026-01-18T17:16:26.415372509Z","close_reason":"Implemented Registration type with RAII deregistration, ReactorHandle trait, and comprehensive tests","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-553y","depends_on_id":"asupersync-uxt9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-01-27T06:20:42Z","created_by":"import"}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-55et","title":"Handle recording limits and graceful degradation","description":"## Overview

Handle out-of-memory and disk-full conditions during trace recording gracefully.

## Requirements

### Recording Limits
```rust
pub struct RecorderConfig {
    /// Maximum events to record before stopping.
    /// Default: None (unlimited)
    pub max_events: Option<u64>,

    /// Maximum memory for buffered events (streaming writer bypasses this).
    /// Default: 100MB
    pub max_memory: usize,

    /// Maximum file size for trace file.
    /// Default: 1GB
    pub max_file_size: u64,

    /// Action when limit reached.
    pub on_limit: LimitAction,
}

pub enum LimitAction {
    /// Stop recording, keep what we have.
    StopRecording,

    /// Drop oldest events (ring buffer mode).
    DropOldest,

    /// Fail loudly (panic in debug, log error in release).
    Fail,

    /// Call user callback for decision.
    Callback(Box<dyn Fn(LimitReached) -> LimitAction>),
}
```

### Graceful Handling
```rust
impl StreamingTraceWriter {
    fn write_event(&mut self, event: &TraceEvent) -> io::Result<()> {
        // Check file size limit
        if self.bytes_written + estimated_size > self.config.max_file_size {
            match self.config.on_limit {
                LimitAction::StopRecording => {
                    tracing::warn!(
                        events = %self.events_written,
                        bytes = %self.bytes_written,
                        "Trace recording stopped: file size limit"
                    );
                    return Ok(());  // Silently stop
                }
                LimitAction::Fail => {
                    return Err(io::Error::new(
                        io::ErrorKind::Other,
                        "Trace file size limit exceeded"
                    ));
                }
                // ...
            }
        }
        // ... write event
    }
}
```

### Disk Full Handling
- Detect ENOSPC errors
- Close file gracefully with partial trace
- Log clear warning with recovery instructions

## Acceptance Criteria
1. RecorderConfig with all limit options
2. LimitAction enum with 4 strategies
3. Graceful stop on file size limit
4. Graceful handling of disk full
5. Ring buffer mode for limited memory
6. Tests for all limit conditions

