 {"id":"asupersync-dyk","title":"Implement two-phase oneshot channel with reserve/commit","description":"## Purpose
Implement a cancel-safe oneshot channel - a single-use channel for exactly one message. Essential for request/response patterns, futures that return values, and one-time coordination.

## Oneshot vs MPSC
| Feature | Oneshot | MPSC |
|---------|---------|------|
| Messages | Exactly 1 | Many |
| Producers | 1 | Many |
| Consumers | 1 | 1 |
| Use case | Return values, replies | Streams, queues |

## Two-Phase Oneshot Model

```rust
pub fn oneshot<T>() -> (Sender<T>, Receiver<T>);

pub struct Sender<T> {
    inner: Arc<OnceCell<T>>,
    obligation_id: Option<ObligationId>,  // Created on reserve
}

pub struct Receiver<T> {
    inner: Arc<OnceCell<T>>,
}

pub struct SendPermit<T> {
    sender: Sender<T>,  // Takes ownership
    obligation_id: ObligationId,
}
```

### Sender API
```rust
impl<T> Sender<T> {
    /// Reserve the send. Cancel-safe.
    pub fn reserve(self, cx: &mut Cx<'_>) -> SendPermit<T> {
        // Create obligation
        // Return permit (consumes sender)
    }

    /// Convenience: reserve + send in one step (still two-phase internally)
    pub fn send(self, cx: &mut Cx<'_>, value: T) -> Result<(), T> {
        self.reserve(cx).send(value)
    }
}

impl<T> SendPermit<T> {
    /// Commit the send. Consumes permit.
    pub fn send(self, value: T) {
        // Write to OnceCell
        // Resolve obligation as Committed
        // Wake receiver
    }

    /// Abort. Consumes permit.
    pub fn abort(self) {
        // Resolve obligation as Aborted
        // Receiver will get RecvError::Closed
    }
}
```

### Receiver API
```rust
impl<T> Receiver<T> {
    /// Wait for the value. Cancel-safe.
    pub async fn recv(self, cx: &mut Cx<'_>) -> Result<T, RecvError> {
        // Wait for value to be present
        // Can be cancelled cleanly
        // Return value on success
    }

    /// Try to receive without waiting.
    pub fn try_recv(self) -> Result<T, TryRecvError> {
        // Return immediately if available
        // Otherwise TryRecvError::Empty or TryRecvError::Closed
    }
}
```

## Common Pattern: Task Results
```rust
// Spawn task that returns a value
let (tx, rx) = oneshot::channel();
scope.spawn(cx, async move |cx| {
    let result = compute_something(cx).await;
    tx.send(cx, result);
});

// Later, await the result
let value = rx.recv(cx).await?;
```

## Cancellation Scenarios
| Scenario | Behavior |
|----------|----------|
| Sender dropped before send | Receiver gets RecvError::Closed |
| Receiver dropped before recv | Sender send succeeds (value dropped) |
| Cancel during recv wait | Clean abort, can retry or close |
| Sender reserve then cancelled | Permit dropped, aborts send |

## Invariant Support
- **Exactly once**: OnceCell ensures value sent at most once
- **Obligation tracking**: SendPermit is an obligation
- **Cancel-safety**: Cancellation at any point is clean

## Comparison to std/tokio
| Feature | std/tokio oneshot | Asupersync oneshot |
|---------|-------------------|-------------------|
| Send cancellation | Send can fail | Two-phase reserve/commit |
| Recv cancellation | Loses sender on cancel | Clean abort |
| Obligation tracking | None | SendPermit is obligation |

## Testing Requirements
1. Basic send/recv
2. Reserve then send
3. Reserve then abort
4. Sender dropped (receiver gets error)
5. Receiver dropped (sender value dropped)
6. Cancel during recv wait
7. try_recv empty and ready cases

## References
- asupersync_plan_v4.md: §6.5 Two-Phase Operations
- tokio::sync::oneshot (reference but different semantics)
- futures::channel::oneshot

## Acceptance Criteria
- `reserve` is cancel-safe (no value moved/committed until commit).
- Dropping the permit aborts deterministically and is trace-visible.
- Receiver behavior is well-defined under cancellation (no leaks, no silent drops).
- Unit + E2E tests cover cancellation during reserve and during commit.
